<span id="freeTextContainer1425710908276619204">Lucyna doesn&apos;t feel anything. She is a bringer, her main goal is to bring people to heaven.<br/><br/>She knows when something is wrong, however, when she feels something. Like really <i>feels</i> something. All because of James. <br/><br/>She broke the rules. She promised Max, James&apos; father, that she would take of James while he grieved for his father. Not that she could do anything, really, but watch him. As she spends more time observing James, she finally comes to the conclusion that can&apos;t be true.<br/><br/>Lucyna is in love.<br/><br/>Suc</span>
  <span id="freeText1425710908276619204" style="display:none">Lucyna doesn't feel anything. She is a bringer, her main goal is to bring people to heaven.<br /><br />She knows when something is wrong, however, when she feels something. Like really <i>feels</i> something. All because of James. <br /><br />She broke the rules. She promised Max, James' father, that she would take of James while he grieved for his father. Not that she could do anything, really, but watch him. As she spends more time observing James, she finally comes to the conclusion that can't be true.<br /><br />Lucyna is in love.<br /><br />Such a good book! The beginning was emotion-less, but it perfectly suited what was happening. Lucyna couldn't feel anything, so the reader didn't feel anything. As she began to grow feelings for James, so does the reader. Beautiful work for a stand-alone novel! Very original story, too. </span>
